@NODE "intro" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}Introduction@{UB}
@{B}============@{UB}

This program is meant to be configured as picture viewer in directory tools
like DirOpus or DosControl. It shows the doubleclicked picture in a
borderless window on the specified custom screen. The remarkable about this
program is that it reads the whole directory the picture is in and you can
then choose other pictures out of this directory from a menu or by pressing
the cursor keys.

PicShow can also be used as a simple slide show program. It can display
pictures either in sort order or randomly. When run on its own screen there
are also some nice blend effects.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "install" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}Installation@{UB}
@{B}============@{UB}

PicShow does not require an installation. Just copy the entire directory to
your harddrive. The supplied Installer script will install the needed PicShow
files into several directories on your boot drive. If you want more details,
please read on.

The files in detail:

PicShow                   main program for generic 68000 processors
PicShow.040               main program for 68040 or better
PicShow.wos               main program for PowerPC, WarpOS
PicShow.elf               main program for PowerPC, PowerUP
PicShow.keys              keyboard mapping for PicShow
PicShowNav.iff            skin picture for PicShow's navigation panel
SlideShow.info            project icon that calls PicShow as a slide show
PicShowTem                program to create a template skin picture
JoinPictures              program to connect several iff pictures to one
                          wide picture.
GetModeID                 small utility to determine the mode ID of a
                          screen mode.
PicShow_xx.guide          this manual (xx = language)
catalogs                  contains ready-to-use translations for PicShow
translations              contains source files to create other catalogs
Install                   Installer script to install PicShow
PicShow.jpg               Backdrop picture for the Installer


@{B}Manual Installation@{UB}
@{B}===================@{UB}

1. Copy the PicShow executable somewhere where your directory tool can
   find it. A good place is the C or the Utilities directory.

2. Copy the catalogs directory either into Locale: or into the same
   directory as the PicShow executable.

   Use the picshow.cd file to create your own translation. If you do not
   need to create another translation, delete it.

   Note: new catalog files must have version 2. PicShow insists on exactly
         this version number !

3. If you want to redefine the function keys, you need to create a file
   called PicShow.keys in one of the following directories:

   -  S:
   -  ENV: or ENVARC:
   -  the directory the PicShow program is in
   -  the directory PicShow is started from (e.g. where the pictures live)

   You can take the @{"provided file" LINK "PicShow.keys/MAIN"} as an Example.

   See the section about @{"key bindings" LINK "keys"} to learn about the contents of the file.

4. Copy the skin file PicShowNav.iff to the same directory as the PicShow
   program. If you choose another location, you must @{"configure PicShow" LINK "config" 109} to
   find it. Otherwise the @{"navigation panel" LINK "nav"} will not be usable.

5. The PicShowTem and JoinPictures programs are only needed, if you want to
   create your own skins for the navigation panel. Copy them to where your
   utilities live.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "funct" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}Possible functions@{UB}
@{B}==================@{UB}

The following functions can be used with PicShow. Usually all functions can
be used as Shell parameters or tooltypes, key definitions, navigation panel
buttons or ARexx commands.

  Option     Short  Type       Description

  FILE         FI  (string)    Set directory to load
  PUBSCREEN    PU  (string)    Choose new public screen
  PATTERN      PA  (string)    Set file name pattern
  FLASH        FL  (switch)    Flash screeb when directory is complete
  CHECK        CH  (switch)    Do not check file types
  DELAY        DE  (number)    Set delay time for slide show
  SCREEN       SC  (switch)    Open custom screen
  BACKGROUND   BG  (string)    Choose background color @{"(more)" LINK "f_background"}
  PORT         PO  (string)    ARexx port name
  MODEID       MI  (number)    Set new screen mode ID @{"(more)" LINK "f_modeid"}
  DEPTH        DP  (number)    Set new screen depth
  SCRMODE      MD  (string)    Choose screen mode @{"(more)" LINK "f_scrmode"}
  QUIET        QE  (switch)    Disable error messages
  CLOSEWB      WB  (switch)    Close Workbench screen when custom screen is open
  REQ          RE  (switch)    Request new directory
  KEYS         KE  (string)    Load new key definition file
  SCALE        SL  (string)    Turn on scaling @{"(more)" LINK "f_scale"}
  INTERPOL     IN  (switch)    Turn on interpolation
  INFO         IF  (switch)    Deactivate info bubble
  CACHE        CA  (number)    Set cache size
  BLEND        BL  (string)    Choose blend mode @{"(more)" LINK "f_blend"}
  BLENDTIME    BT  (number)    Set blend time
  POINTER      PT  (switch)    Hide mouse pointer
  SHUFFLE      SH  (switch)    Activate random mode
  NAV          NA  (switch)    Open / close navigation panel
  NAVSKIN      NS  (string)    Load skin for navigation panel @{"(more)" LINK "nav"}
  NAVBUTTONS   NB  (string)    Arrange buttons on navigation panel @{"(more)" LINK "nav"}
  CLOSEGAD     CG  (switch)    Enable close gadget
  ANIMATE      AN  (switch)    Start animation forward @{"(more)" LINK "f_animate"}
  STICKYPOPUP  SM  (switch)    Make popup menu sticky @{"(more)" LINK "f_stickypopup"}
  QUITOLD      QU  (switch)    Quit PicShow @{"(more)" LINK "f_quitold"}
  KEEPZOOM     KZ  (switch)    Keep zoom factor
  JPEG         JP  (switch)    Save pictures as JPEG
  REQIFEMPTY   RI  (switch)    Open file requester if directory is empty
  SHOWINFO     SI  (switch)    Show info on top of picture
  PRELOAD      PL  (number)    Set number of pictures to preload
  JPEGQUALITY  JQ  (number)    Set quality value for saved JPEG files
  NEWPORT      NP  (switch)    Create a new port name for each invocation
  BORDER       BO  (number)    Set border size
  ALL          RU  (switch)    Read directories recursively
  DETACH       DT  (switch)    Start PicShow in the background
  PPCSCALE     PP  (switch)    Let the PPC do all scaling (PPC only)

  Notes: 

   o  switches can be switched off by either the parameter OFF or by the
      prefix NO or DONT. E.g. REQ OFF or NOREQ both don't show a requester.

   o  all options can be used as commands, too. When given without a
      parameter
       - switches are toggled
       - strings and numbers open a requester for the user.


  Command    Short Description

  MOVE         MO  Move the navigation panel
  QUIT         QU  Quit PicShow
  CLOSE        CL  Close navigation panel
  PREFS        PF  Open preferences window
  MENU         ME  Open menu
  INVERTBG     IV  Invert background color
  SAVE         SA  Save picture
  HARDCOPY     HA  Save hardcopy @{"(more)" LINK "f_hardcopy"}
  PREV         PV  Show previous picture
  NEXT         NE  Show next picture
  BACK         BA  Browse back in cache
  FORWARD      FO  Browse forward in cache
  RANDOM       RA  Show random picture
  STOP         ST  Pause slide show
  PUBSCR       PU  Choose new public screen
  HELP         HE  Open help window
  ZOOMIN       ZI  Zoom in
  ZOOMOUT      ZO  Zoom out
  ZOOMNORM     ZN  Do not zoom @{"(more)" LINK "f_zoomnorm"}
  NEXTMULTI    NM  Show next picture in multi picture file
  PREVMULTI    PM  Show previous picture in multi picture file
  FLUSH        FU  Flush pictures in cache
  ABOUT        AB  Show information about PicShow.
  ROTATEL      RL  Rotate left 90°
  ROTATER      RR  Rotate right 90°
  FLIPX        FX  Mirror horizontally
  FLIPY        FY  Mirror vertically
  COLORS       CO  Change colors
  DELETE       DL  Delete current picture
  DELQUIET     DQ  Delete current picture quietly
  SCROLLUP     LU  Scroll picture up
  SCROLLDOWN   LD  Scroll picture down
  SCROLLLEFT   LL  Scroll picture left
  SCROLLRIGHT  LR  Scroll picture right
  SAVEPREFS    SP  Save preferences
  SHELL        SE  Execute a shell command @{"(more)" LINK "f_shell"}
  KEY          KY  Rebind key @{"(more)" LINK "f_key"}
  SCROLL       SR  Scroll picture
  ZOOM         ZF  Set zoom factor
  ZOOMFACTOR   ZF  Set zoom factor
  RECORDKEY    RC  Record key
  SAVEKEYS     SK  Save key definitions
  PARENT       PR  Read parent directory
  PRINT        PN  Print picture @{"(more)" LINK "f_print"}
  MARK         MA  Mark
  COPY         CP  Copy
  PASTE        PS  Paste
  SELECTALL    AL  Select all
  CLEARSEL     CS  Clear selected
  SIZE         SZ  Change Size @{"(more)" LINK "f_size"}
  BESTMODE     BE  Set screen mode according to picture dimensions
  CACHEMENU    CM  Choose picture from cache
  ICONIFY      IC  Iconify
  HIDE         HI  Iconify
  SHOW         SH  Uniconify
  INVERT       IR  Invert picture
  GREYSCALES   GS  Extract grey scales
  GREY         GS  Extract grey scales
  GRAYSCALES   GS  Extract grey scales
  GRAY         GS  Extract grey scales
  EXTRED       RD  Extract red
  RED          RD  Extract red
  EXTGREEN     GR  Extract green
  GREEN        GR  Extract green
  EXTBLUE      BU  Extract blue
  BLUE         BU  Extract blue
  CYCLE        CY  Cycle red -> green -> blue
  REMOVERED    XR  Remove red
  REMRED       XR  Remove red
  TURQ         TU  Remove red
  REMOVEGREEN  XG  Remove green
  REMGREEN     XG  Remove green
  PURPLE       PE  Remove green
  REMOVEBLUE   XB  Remove blue
  REMBLUE      XB  Remove blue
  YELLOW       YE  Remove blue
  COMMANDS     CD  Show a list of all available commands and options
  BACKDROP     BD  Save current picture as desktop wallpaper @{"(more)" LINK "f_backdrop"}
  DELETEARGS   DA  Discard the recorded changes (ARexx only)
  NEWARGS      AR  Start to record changes (ARexx only) @{"(more)" LINK "f_newargs"}
  ENDARGS      EA  Apply the recorded changes (ARexx only)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_hardcopy" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}HARDCOPY@{UB}

Syntax:  HARDCOPY

Description:

Save a hardcopy of the current screen. This command works different in
window and screen mode: in window mode the part of the picture that is
shown on the screen is saved. In screen mode a hardcopy of the entire
screen is saved (the part of the picture that fits on the screen plus
frames).

Use the JPEG switch to choose whether the picture is saved as IFF or JPEG.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_background" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}BACKGROUND@{UB}

Syntax:  BACKGROUND [color]

Description:

Set the background color for PicShow's custom screen. Format is six
hexadecimal numbers: rrggbb
 rr = amount of red color (00 - ff)
 gg = amount of green color (00 - ff)
 bb = amount of blue color (00 - ff)
Default is 000000 (black).

If no color is given, a colorwheel is opened.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_scrmode" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}SCRMODE@{UB}

Syntax:  SCRMODE <dimensions>

Description:

Enter the desired screen dimensions in the form WIDTHxHEIGHTxDEPTH

Example: 640x480x8

PicShow uses the BestModeID function to find a screen mode with these
dimensions.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_scale" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}SCALE@{UB}

Syntax:  SCALE
         SCALE ON
         SCALE OFF
         SCALE DOWN
         SCALE FILL

Description:

SCALE             Cycles through the choices

SCALE ON          Enables scaling. Pictures will be scaled to fit the
                  screen size.

SCALE DOWN        Scale only down (do not enlarge small pictures).

SCALE FILL        Scale up picture to totaly fill the screen. This maybe
                  useful to check whether a picture (or part of) is usable
                  as a wallpaper.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_blend" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}BLEND@{UB}

Syntax:  BLEND [effect]

Description:

Enable/Disable blend effects. Choose one of the following:

NONE     disable blending (this is the default)
RANDOM   randomly use one of all blend effects
RANDOM1  randomly use one of UP to LEFTUP2
RANDOM2  randomly use DIFFUSE or DIFFUSE2

UP
DOWN
LEFT
RIGHT
RIGHTDOWN
RIGHTUP
LEFTDOWN
LEFTUP
RIGHTDOWN2
RIGHTUP2
LEFTDOWN2
LEFTUP2

DIFFUSE
DIFFUSE2

Without parameter the command opens a window to let the user choose an
effect.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_zoomnorm" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}ZOOMNORM@{UB}

Syntax:  ZOOMNORM

Description:

Show the picture in its normal size. This undoes the ZOOMIN / ZOOMOUT
commands. Note that the picture is not necessarily shown in 100% of its
size but in the size given by the SCALE / DOWN / FILL options. Use the
ZOOMFACTOR command to set the zoom factor to 100%.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_animate" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}ANIMATE@{UB}

Syntax:  ANIMATE
         ANIMATE ON
         ANIMATE F
         ANIMATE FORWARD
         ANIMATE B
         ANIMATE BACK
         ANIMATE OFF

Description:

Start or stop the animation. Animation will show each picture in a
multi-image file after another. This only works with picture.datatype
V45 and an appropriate picture class (e.g. gif.datatype V44,
WarpTIFF.datatype).

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_quitold" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}QUITOLD@{UB}

Description:

Makes PicShow more usable in web browsers. Usualy when PicShow is called a
second time, it sends its parameters to the first copy and quits. But web
browsers delete the temporary file after the viewer quits, so when the
first PicShow tries to load the picture, it has already been deleted. With
this option the second copy of PicShow tells the first one to quit and
shows the picture itself.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_stickypopup" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}STICKYPOPUP@{UB}

Syntax:  STICKYPOPUP
         STICKYPOPUP ON
         STICKYPOPUP OFF

Description:

Tell PicShow to keep the popup menu open till the mouse button is pressed a
second time (like with MagicMenu).

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_key" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}KEY@{UB}

Syntax:  KEY=<key binding>

Description:

Rebind one key. May be specified multiple times for different keys. Read
the section about @{"key bindings" LINK "keys"} for an explanation of <key
binding>.

Example:  KEY=X=QUIT     enable the key X to quit PicShow

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_shell" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}SHELL@{UB}

Syntax:  SHELL <command line>

Description:

In the command line of the SHELL command the following placeholders can be
used to include information about the current picture:

%p   Path
%f   File name
%m   Main part of file name (without extension)
%e   Extension of the file name
%n   Number (starting with 1 at the top of the list)
%w   Width
%h   Height
%d   Depth
%t   Type
%q   ARexx port name
%r   public screen name

The placeholders can contain any modifiers that a C format string accepts
(for example %04n for a 4 digit number to the left padded with 0's),

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_modeid" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}MODEID@{UB}

Syntax:  MODEID <id>

Description:

Decimal mode ID of the screenmode to use. Default is same as Workbench.

To determine the mode ID you can use the included program GetModeID. It
lets you choose the screen mode from a requester and prints the
corresponding mode ID to the Shell window or in a dialogue box.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_print" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}PRINT@{UB}

Syntax:  PRINT

Description:

Prints the picture. In the preview window you can choose the following
options:

Print: Whole picture   print the whole picture
       Visible part    print only the visible part of the picture
       Screen          print the entire screen. That is the visible part
                       and the frame around it (only in screen mode).

Size: Choose the size of the picture on the paper.

Center: Choose whether the picture should be horizontaly centered on the
        paper.

Eject page: Choose whether the paper should be ejected after the print.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_size" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}SIZE@{UB}

Syntax:  SIZE

Description:

Opens a window to let the user scale the picture to any size.

The following options can be choosen:

New width / New height : desired size of the picture

Proportional:  New height will be calculated from new width using the
               picture's aspect ratio.

Interpolation: Choose whether interpolation should be used.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_newargs" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}NEWARGS, ENDARGS, DELETEARGS@{UB}


Description:

These are the commands used by PicShow to send its parameters to the first
instance when started a second time. After NEWARGS, all ARexx commands that
change options are not executed at once but stored in an arguments array.
After ENDARGS, all stored arguments are applied in one go. After that the
ARexx commands work as usual again. DELETEARGS is similar to ENDARGS, but
the arguments are not applied but discarded.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "f_backdrop" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}BACKDROP@{UB}

Syntax:  BACKDROP

Description:

Saves the current picture as "Sys:Prefs/Presets/PicShow_Wallpaper" and
changes ENV:WBPattern.prefs to point to the new picture.

This is as if you click on "Use" in the WBPattern prefs program. To make
the change permanent, you have to open WBPattern and click on "Save" (this
saves the changed prefs to ENVARC:WBPattern.prefs).

Note: after you saved the WBPattern, the permanent settings point to 
Sys:Prefs/Presets/PicShow_Wallpaper, so if you use the BACKDROP command
again, the new wallpaper is applied permanently at once (because the same
picture file is replaced by the new one).

The options for dither quality, color quality and layout must be set in the
WBPattern program. PicShow uses defaults here. To get the best quality you
should scale the picture in PicShow and move it around until you see the
wallpaper as it should be before you use the BACKDROP command.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "config" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}Configuration@{UB}
@{B}=============@{UB}


There are three ways to configure PicShow:


@{B}The file PicShow.defaults@{UB}

This file specifies the default values for all configuration items. It is
read first and will be overridden by parameters or tooltypes.

It is loaded from S:, ENV:, PROGDIR: and the current directory. The latter
overrides the former.


@{B}Shell parameters@{UB}

When called from the DOS Shell the configuration items can be given as
parameters.


@{B}Tooltypes@{UB}

If PicShow is started from the Workbench, configuration items can be
entered as tooltypes, either in the program icon or in the picture icon
that is activated first. Tooltypes in the picture icon overide those in the
program icon. Picture icons can be activated by shift-click or by
specifying PicShow as default tool.


For a list of the available configuration items please look on the
@{"functions" LINK "funct"} page.



@{B}Creating a picture file type in DirOpus Magellan@{UB}
@{B}================================================@{UB}

Just follow these steps:

- choose menu @{B}Settings / File Types@{UB}
- click on @{B}Add@{UB}
- enter @{B}Name: picture@{UB}
- enter @{B}ID:   pict@{UB}
- enter @{B}Pri:  0@{UB}
- click on @{B}Add@{UB}
- choose @{B}Match DT Group@{UB}
- enter @{B}pict@{UB}
- click on @{B}Use@{UB}
- choose @{B}Double-click@{UB}
- click on @{B}Edit@{UB}
- click on @{B}Add@{UB}
- choose @{B}AmigaDOS@{UB}
- enter @{B}c:PicShow {f} pubscreen {Qs} pattern ~(#?.info)@{UB}
- switch on @{B}Run asynchronously@{UB}
- click on @{B}Use@{UB}
- click on @{B}Use@{UB}
- click on @{B}Save@{UB}

Instead of c:PicShow you must enter the path to where you installed
PicShow. Behind the program name you can configure all settings as
described @{"above" LINK "config" 1}.

For more information please read the @{"DOpus manual" LINK "DOpus5:help/dopus5.guide/File Type Editor"} !


@ENDNODE
@NODE "usage" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}Usage@{UB}
@{B}=====@{UB}

This section describes the commands that can be accesed via the keyboard.

All commands can also be called from the pull down menu. Move the mouse
pointer to the top edge of the screen and press the right mouse button to
activate the menu.

If the PicShow windows is opened on the Workbench or on a public screen,
you can grip the window on the lower right corner and pull it larger or
smaller.


NOTE: these are the default keys. Read the section about @{"key bindings" LINK "keys"} to
      learn how to change them.

o  Quit PicShow
   -  double click into the window or
   -  press the ESC key or
   -  press Q

o  Show the next picture
   -  press the cursor down key or
   -  press the cursor right key or

o  Show the previous picture
   -  press the cursor up key or
   -  press the cursor left key or
   -  press backspace (the <- key above return)

o  Show a random picture
   -  press space bar or
   -  press return

o  Show the previous picture in the cache (retrace)
   -  press R

o  Show the next picture in the cache (undo retrace)
   -  press T

o  Start/stop animation if there are multiple pictures in one file
   -  press A

o  Show some infos about the current picture
   -  keep the mouse pointer inside the window and don't move it for
      some time (can be disabled by an option)

o  If the picture is too large to fit into the screen
   -  grab the picture with the left mouse button and move it around.

o  Move the picture around by keyboard
   -  press the cursor keys on the numeric keypad
      (8 = up, 2 = down, 4 = left, 6 = right)

o  Choose a picture from the list
   -  press the right mouse button and hold it down. The list can scroll
      up and down if there are more files than fit into one page. Just
      move the mouse pointer over the arrow(s).
   -  hold down the shift key or press caps lock to only show the pictures
      that currently are loaded in the cache.
   -  The list can be moved faster with the cursor keys:
       left  = top of the list
       right = bottom of the list
       down  = next page
       up    = previous page

o  Read a new directory
   -  Press F1

o  Swap display from Workbench to PicShow's own screen and back
   -  Press F10

o  Invert the background color of PicShow's own screen (e.g. from black
   to white and vice versa)
   -  Press F9

o  Pause / continue slide show
   -  Press P

o  Save the picture as displayed on screen:
   -  Press S

o  Save a hardcopy of the screen:
   -  Press D

   Note: this command works different in window and screen mode:
         in window mode the part of the picture that is shown on the screen
         is saved. In screen mode a hardcopy of the entire screen is saved
         (the part of the picture that fits on screen plus frames).

o  Open/close the navigation panel
   -  Press F5

o  Show a list of all key commands
   -  Press Help

o  Mark a part of the picture with the mouse
   -  Press B

o  Copy the marked part into the clipboard
   -  Press C

o  Show the clipboard
   -  Press V

o  Mark the entire picture
   -  Press [

o  Clear the selection
   -  Press ]

In the example file @{"PicShow.keys" LINK "PicShow.keys/MAIN"} the following additional keys are defined:

o  Copy the displayed picture into RAM:
   -  Press C

   The file name is "pic<number>_<width>x<height>x<depth>.<type>".
   Example: pic0001_640x480x8.ilbm
   This is only an example. Read the section about @{"key bindings" LINK "keys"} for a
   description on how to configure your own shell commands.

o  Enable/disable the info bubble
   -  press I

o  Hide/Show the mouse pointer
   -  press O

o  Read the parent directory
   -  press F2

o  Select a new public screen to open PicShow on
   -  press F6

o  Choose a new background color for PicShow's screen
   -  press F8

o  Choose a new screen mode for PicShow's screen
   -  press M

o  Choose a blend effect for the slide show
   -  press F7

o  Enable/Disable random order for slide show
   -  press H

o  Enable/Disable screen flash after directory read has finished
   -  press F

o  Zoom in
   -  press +
   -  press + on the numeric keypad

o  Zoom out
   -  press -
   -  press - on the numeric keypad

o  Show normal size
   -  press 0

o  Show next picture in multi-image file
   -  press L

o  Show previous picture in multi-image file
   -  press K

o  Mirror the picture on the X axis
   -  press X

o  Mirror the picture on the Y axis
   -  press Y

o  Rotate the picture 90° to the right
   -  press E

o  Rotate the picture 90° to the left
   -  press W


And many more. Press HELP to see the current settings.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "arexx" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}Arexx port@{UB}
@{B}==========@{UB}

The name of the ARexx port is PICSHOW. It can be changed by the parameter
(or tooltype) PORT. If the option NEWPORT is set, the second instance gets
the port PICSHOW.1, the third PICSHOW.2, and so on.

Please look on the @{"functions" LINK "funct"} page for a list of available commands.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "keys" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}Key bindings@{UB}
@{B}============@{UB}

Key bindings are read from the files

-  S:PicShow.keys
-  env:PicShow.keys
-  PROGDIR:PicShow.keys
-  CURRENTDIR:PicShow.keys
-  the file specified by the KEYS function

if they exist. Each file can contain any number of keys, one per line.

Whenever I talk about a <key binding> in this guide, the following format
is meant:

<key>=<command>

Space characters before and after the "=" are ignored.

<key> can be any key description that also a commodity would accept as a
hot key, except qualifiers like shift, alt and ctrl.

Examples:

a, b, c, 1, 2, 3,           Normal keys
numpad 1, numpad 2, enter   Keys on the numeric key pad
f1, f2, f10, help           Function keys
return, del, backspace      Special keys
up, down, left, right       Cursor keys

<command> is what the key should do.

Please look on the @{"functions" LINK "funct"} page for a list of valid commands.

Take a look into the file @{"PicShow.keys" LINK "PicShow.keys/MAIN"} for examples.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "nav" "PicShow V1.29 Guide"
@TOC "main"

@{" Contents " LINK "main"} @{" Intro " LINK "intro"} @{" Install " LINK "install"} @{" Funct " LINK "funct"} @{" Config " LINK "config"} @{" Usage " LINK "usage"} @{" Arexx " LINK "arexx"} @{" Keys " LINK "keys"} @{" Nav " LINK "nav"} @{" Future " LINK "future"}


@{B}The navigation panel@{UB}
@{B}====================@{UB}

The navigation panel allows the user to navigate PicShow with the mouse.
All functions available as key strokes are also available on the navigation
panel. The panel is fully configurable.

The navigation panel is activated by the NAV parameter or tooltype or by
pressing the F5 key.

For a list of valid functions please look at the @{"functions" LINK "funct"} page.


@{B}How to arrange the buttons@{UB}
@{B}--------------------------@{UB}

The button arrangement of the navigation panel can be changed by the
NAVBUTTONS parameter or tooltype. After the keyword follows a list of
functions in the order of appearence. Functions are seperated by comma.
Space characters are not allowed.

The order is from left to right, alternating the top and bottom button.

The MOVE operator must not be used in the arrangement ! It is added
automaticaly on the left and right of the panel.

The default arrangement is CL,QU,BA,PV,FO,NE,ST,RA,RE,PF,ME,IF,SC,IV,SA,HA.


@{B}How to create new skins@{UB}
@{B}-----------------------@{UB}

The default skin is @{"PicShowNav.iff" LINK "PicShowNav.iff/MAIN"} in the same directory as PicShow. You
can specify a different file name or location using the NAVSKIN parameter
or tooltype.

A skin consists of one picture file containing all buttons and their
pressed pendants. The picture starts on the left with the drag bar symbol
and its pressed image. Then the buttons follow, the original on the top and
the pressed image below.

In the default skin the width of the drag bar is 5 pixels and each button
is 25 x 25 dots. Each element has a one pixel frame around it. Note that
the frame is used by both adjacent buttons.

If you want to vary the button size, you must keep the proportions. Use the
supplied program @{"PicShowTem" LINK "nav" 142} to create a template.

If you want to change the order of buttons in the skin or if you want to
omit some unsused buttons, you must create an Icon for the picture file
containing the tooltype BUTTONS. The BUTTONS argument works just like the
@{"NAVBUTTONS" LINK "nav" 81} parameter of PicShow with the only exception that this time the
string must start with the MOVE command.

The default skin order is: MO,NO,QU,CL,RE,PF,ME,SC,IV,SA,HA,PV,NE,BA,FO,
RA,RA,ST,ST,IF,IF,U1,U2,U3,U4,U5,U6,U7,U8,U9,U0,NO

If not all buttons fit into one tooltype line, add another BUTTONS
tooltype. All BUTTONS tooltypes will be concatenated.

Buttons of switches (like INFO, POINTER or RANDOM) or buttons of options
that cycle choices (like SCALE) change their appearence when pressed. In
the skin picture for each appearence a button must exist with the same
function as the original one. All appearences for the same function must
follow each other.


@{B}The PicShowTem program@{UB}
@{B}----------------------@{UB}

The program can be started from Workbench or from the Shell. If called
without parameters it opens a GUI window. It needs the width and hight of
one button and the number of buttons. It then saves a template picture to
the given file name. Currently it does not create an icon for the file.



@{B}The JoinPictures program@{UB}
@{B}------------------------@{UB}

Some programs (e.g. PPaint) have problems working with pictures that are
wider than 1008 pixels. So I have written this programs that joins several
pictures to one expanded one.

It can only be called from the Shell. Syntax is:

JoinPictures <part1> <part2> ... as <big_picture> [nocompress]

All pictures must be in IFF ILBM format.


Parameters:
-----------

FILE/M/A            Enter the file names of the several parts here.

TO=AS/A             Enter the name of the destination picture here.

NOC=NOCOMPRESS/S    Save the destination bitmap uncompressed.


@ENDNODE
